Each card covers all five dimensions — here is the logic behind each chart's decisions, kept in plain language.
Chart 1 — Monthly sales trend (line chart). The line was chosen because sales is a continuous measure over time and the primary question is about
direction and momentum — not about comparing discrete totals. The y-axis starts at zero deliberately. Truncating it at ₹5 crore would make the August 2024 
trough look catastrophically deeper than it is, distorting leadership's reading of volatility. The area fill under the line adds a sense of volume without competing 
with the line itself, kept at 8% opacity so it reads as context rather than data.
Chart 2 — Regional and state performance (horizontal bar). Horizontal orientation was chosen because region and state names are text that reads naturally
left-to-right, not top-to-bottom. Sorting descending by sales means the answer to "who is best?" is always at the top — no scanning required. A map was explicitly rejected: 
four named regions are not geographic polygons, and a choropleth map of India would require correct state boundaries while making bar-length comparison harder. 
Color uses emphasis rather than rainbow: the top bar is solid blue, the rest are light blue. This encodes "South is the leader" pre-attentively without 
assigning arbitrary different colors to regions that have no inherent color identity.
Chart 3 — Category and sub-category profitability (horizontal bar, sorted by profit). Thirteen sub-categories need to be compared on a single profit measure. A treemap 
was considered and rejected because comparing bar lengths is cognitively more accurate than comparing areas. A pie chart with 13 slices would produce illegible thin 
wedges for the smaller Office Supplies sub-categories. The horizontal bar sorted by profit descending makes rank and magnitude immediately readable. Color encodes 
parent category — all Technology sub-categories are the same blue, all Furniture sub-categories the same amber — so color tells you category membership and position 
tells you rank. Two different dimensions of information, two different visual channels.
Chart 4 — Customer segment return risk (bar with reference line). The reference line at 4.55% (the estate average) is the design decision that transforms this chart 
from a ranking into a diagnostic. Without it, the viewer sees three bars of different heights and must decide what counts as "high." With it, the viewer immediately 
sees that Home Office is above average and the other two are below. Color is semantic — red means above-average risk, amber means near-average, green means below — so 
the chart answers "which segment has a problem?" before any number is read. Using the same colour for all three bars would have forced the viewer to read and compare 
numbers rather than receive an immediate visual answer.
Chart 5 — Shipping delay by mode (stacked bar). The stacked form was chosen specifically because it answers two questions simultaneously: how many orders does each
mode handle (total bar height) and what proportion of those orders are delayed (internal segment colour). A 100% stacked bar would normalise all bars to the same height, 
hiding the critical fact that Standard Class handles 2,435 orders versus Same Day's 241 — making both look equally significant. The colour ramp from green to red follows 
the natural traffic-light convention so the severity of each delay bucket is encoded in the colour itself, not just its label. A viewer can identify the problematic mode
(Standard Class) and the problematic buckets (amber slow, red very slow) in a single glance without reading any text.
